WORK SEXUAL HARASSMENT MYTHS

According to the Australian Human Rights Commission, in 2018, 23% of women & 16% of men have experienced sexual harassment at work in Australia.  Here are 8 common myths often used to justify sexually harassing behaviour:

1: People who get offended just can’t take a joke or are too sensitive. 
2. It’s just boys being boy.
3: You should take it as a compliment. (If unwelcome, it’s not a compliment).
4: They’re one of our top performers... 5: It’s all gone too far – we can’t say or do anything these days! 
6: I don’t want to get involved – it’s none of my business.
7: It only happens to [straight-cis] women. 
8: It’s mainly just senior men taking advantage of their secretaries. 
Sexual harassment in the workplace is about power.  It is disrespectful, regardless of gender, sexual orientation, cultural background, age etc.

On a personal note, I recall an incident of harassment when I was a young manager of about 28y old.  One of my older male colleagues ( who reported to me) grabbed me and popped me on his knee.  He then jiggled me up and down like a child, squuezing me & laughing at "how scrumptious" I looked 😤. Needless to say, I was outraged and set very firm boundaries.  He never touched me again, but it has stuck in my mind as a huge act of disrespect and attempted disempowerment. 
Source: www.dca.org.au/research/project/myth-busting-sexual-harassment-work
